iv interveniert.  aIn place of the entanglement of person and work that so strongly marks the artistic work of Andy Warhol, and settles it in the usual Pop Art context, Mèlanie-Chantal Deiss locates it within the cultural context of America's post-war period. Viewed from this perspective, Warhol's work - which tends to be classified as superficial and ahistorical - exhibits unexpectedly serious engagements with concerns of the 1950s and 1960s. Throughout his image series, expressive, somewhat ambivalent narrative strands from America's post-war period unfurl, which transmit a concrete image, as a kind of written historical document. Warhol's visualized narration ultimately culminates in a cultural critique, which treats America not just as a stage of images, but also as site of contemplation of a cultural imaginary, in which art can critically and productively intervene.  afunded by Swiss National Science Foundation (SNSF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPop artzUnited Statesy20th century. 4aAmerika. 4aAmerikanische Kunst. 4aAmerikanistik. 4aBildwissenschaft. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aKunst. 4aKunstwissenschaft. 4aNachkriegszeit. 4aPop Art. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAmerican Art.  aAmerican Studies.  aArt.  aCultural History.  aFine Arts.  aPop Art.  aPost-war.  aVisual Studies.2 aSwiss National Science Foundation (SNSF)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2015 Part 2z978311076664608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of 